<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This tiny ornamental shrub is native to Mexico, Guatemala and Honduras, but widely cultivated elsewhere in the subtropics. It easily self-seeds and sometimes naturalises where introduced, for instance, in Hawaii and New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, R" journalOrPublisher="Auckland Botanical Society Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="74 - 78" refId="B6509021" refString="Gardner, R, de Lange, P, 1996. Naturalized plants in New Zealand: new or noteworthy records. Auckland Botanical Society Journal 51 (2): 74 - 78" title="Naturalized plants in New Zealand: new or noteworthy records" volume="51" year="1996">Gardner and de Lange 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, R" journalOrPublisher="Auckland Botanical Society Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="65 - 65" refId="B6509012" refString="Gardner, R, 1998. Streamsides of false heather (Cuphea hyssopifolia, Lythraceae). Auckland Botanical Society Journal 53 (2): 65 - 65" title="Streamsides of false heather (Cuphea hyssopifolia, Lythraceae)" volume="53" year="1998">Gardner 1998</bibRefCitation>
). In the Canary Islands, it was previously reported from La Palma (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509388" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2016. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 35" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="35" year="2016">Otto and Verloove 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">In December 2018, few plants were noticed in cracks of concrete in a residential area in La Quinta.</paragraph>
